Today I spent a few hours hardening my GitHub Actions workflow for my blog.
The workflow takes raw notes from a drafts folder, sends them to a Gemini LLM,
and publishes a polished blog post automatically.

Key things I did:
- Split the schedule gate into its own job so the publish job is fully skipped
- Fixed a potential shell injection issue where LLM output was interpolated directly in bash
- Switched from Gemini 2.5 Pro to 2.5 Flash for faster/cheaper runs
- Moved tags into Jekyll frontmatter instead of leaving them in the post body
- Scoped git add to specific directories instead of using -A

It was a good reminder that even "working" CI pipelines deserve a security review.
The injection risk was subtle -- the LLM title went straight into shell variables.
Writing to temp files first and reading back is a simple but effective fix.

Next up: maybe add a PR-based review step before auto-publishing.
